[## LECTURE 4.3 — CLOUDWATCH LOG GROUPS WITH 7-YEAR RETENTION]

57
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your database audit log is one piece.
But what about application logs? API access logs?
Kubernetes audit logs?
They all need to be stored immutably with appropriate retention.

58
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
For SOC 2, audit logs typically need seven-year retention.
CloudWatch can do this, but you need to configure it correctly.

59
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
First, define your log groups in Terraform.
Create a local map of log group names and retention days.

60
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Audit logs get 2555 days retention. That is seven years.
This includes forward slash financial-rag forward slash audit.
Forward slash financial-rag forward slash api-access.
Forward slash financial-rag forward slash auth.
And forward slash financial-rag forward slash db-audit.

61
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Operational logs get 365 days retention.
This includes forward slash financial-rag forward slash api.
Forward slash financial-rag forward slash agent.
And forward slash financial-rag forward slash ingestion.

62
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
The EKS cluster audit log also gets 365 days retention.
Its name is forward slash aws forward slash eks forward slash financial-rag-prod forward slash cluster.

63
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Create each log group using for_each over the local map.
Set retention_in_days and kms_key_id.
Tag the groups with Control equals CC7.5.

64
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Now create an IAM policy that denies log group deletion.
This is critical. A user with logs colon DeleteLogGroup can wipe your audit trail.
The policy explicitly denies DeleteLogGroup, DeleteLogStream, DeleteRetentionPolicy.

65
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Also deny PutRetentionPolicy for groups that already have seven-year retention.
This prevents someone from shortening the retention period.

66
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
For the strongest protection, apply this as a Service Control Policy in AWS Organizations.
An SCP applies to all IAM users and roles in the account, including the root user.
Even AWS support cannot override an SCP.

67
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Create the SCP with the same deny statements.
Attach it to your production account.
Now audit log deletion is impossible.

68
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Now configure Fluent Bit to send logs to the right groups.
Create a ConfigMap in the logging namespace.

69
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
For API access logs, tail the container logs for the API pod.
Filter for logs containing event_type equals api_request or auth_failure.
Output to the forward slash financial-rag forward slash audit log group.

70
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
For agent logs, output to the forward slash financial-rag forward slash agent log group.
One-year retention.
For ingestion logs, output to the forward slash financial-rag forward slash ingestion log group.

71
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Verify the logs are flowing and retention is set correctly.
aws logs describe-log-groups for the forward slash financial-rag prefix.
Query logGroupName and retentionInDays.

72
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Verify KMS encryption on the audit group.
aws logs describe-log-groups for forward slash financial-rag forward slash audit.
Query kmsKeyId. It should return your KMS key ARN.

73
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Test that logs are being written.
aws logs tail forward slash financial-rag forward slash audit dash dash since five minutes.
You should see API request logs appearing.

74
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Save the log group configuration as evidence.
Run the describe command and output to cloudwatch-log-groups dot json.

75
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Your lab exercise is to create the CloudWatch log groups.
Configure retention and KMS encryption.
Apply the SCP to prevent deletion.

76
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Verify that logs are flowing and retention is set correctly.
In the next lecture, we will configure S3 Object Lock.
For truly immutable archive storage.

