[## LECTURE 4.5 — PGAUDIT: DATABASE-LEVEL SQL AUDIT LOGGING]

98
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your application logs are one thing.
But what about direct database access?
A DBA connecting with psql. A compromised pod that finds database credentials.

99
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
A developer running a one-off query in production.
None of these appear in your application logs.
PostgreSQL has an extension called pgAudit that solves this.

100
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
pgAudit captures every SQL statement executed against the database.
Regardless of who ran it, from what client, or through what connection.

101
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
For RDS, enable pgAudit through the parameter group.
Update the parameter group with shared_preload_libraries equals pgaudit comma pg_stat_statements.

102
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Set pgaudit.log equals ddl, role, read, write.
This logs data definition language, role statements, reads, and writes.
Set pgaudit.log_parameter equals one to log query parameters.

103
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Set pgaudit.log_relation equals one to log table names.
Apply the parameter group and reboot the RDS instance.
The reboot is required to load the shared library.

104
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
After reboot, connect to the database and enable the extension.
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgaudit.
Verify the configuration with SHOW pgaudit.log.

105
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Now run a test query. SELECT COUNT asterisk FROM analysis_history.
Then check the logs.

106
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Here is what pgAudit emits.
A log line with AUDIT colon SESSION.
Then the statement ID, substatement, class, command, and the full SQL text.

107
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Every SELECT, INSERT, CREATE, GRANT is logged.
With timestamp, database user, and the exact SQL.

108
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Configure RDS to publish these logs to CloudWatch.
In the Terraform for the RDS instance, set enabled_cloudwatch_logs_exports.
Include postgresql and upgrade.

109
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Now verify that pgAudit logs are in CloudWatch.
aws logs tail forward slash aws forward slash rds forward slash instance forward slash financial-rag-prod forward slash postgresql.
Filter pattern AUDIT.

110
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Query for specific access to analysis_history.
aws logs filter-log-events with filter pattern analysis_history.
The output shows every query that touched that table.

111
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Save the log group configuration as evidence.
aws logs describe-log-groups for the RDS log group.
Output to pgaudit-log-groups dot json.

112
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Your lab exercise is to enable pgAudit on your RDS instance.
Run various SQL operations and verify they appear in the logs.
Configure log export to CloudWatch.

113
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
In the next lecture, we will run monthly integrity verification.
And generate an audit report for your evidence package.

