[## LECTURE 4.6 — MONTHLY INTEGRITY VERIFICATION AND AUDIT REPORT]

114
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
A SOC 2 Type II auditor will test whether your audit logs have been tampered with.
If you wait for the audit to run this verification,
you are operating blind for six to twelve months.

115
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Any tampering during the observation period could invalidate your entire Type II report.
Run verification monthly.
Detect tampering as soon as it occurs.

116
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Generate a report that proves continuous integrity throughout the observation period.

117
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Create a function generate_monthly_integrity_report.
It takes a session, signer, report year, report month, and evidence bucket.

118
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
First, verify the hash chain integrity for the month.
Call chain_repo dot verify_chain_integrity with start_date and end_date.

119
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Second, count records by agent_type and analysis_style.
Include average latency and error count.
This gives you usage metrics for the month.

120
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Third, check S3 archive completeness.
For each day in the month, check if the daily export exists.
If any day is missing, note it in the report.

121
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Fourth, assemble the report.
Include total records, error count, error rate, chain integrity status,
signature validity, records verified, and missing days.

122
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Fifth, upload the report to the immutable evidence bucket.
Use Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode with seven-year retention.

123
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Schedule this to run on the first day of each month at 2 AM UTC.
The monthly integrity report becomes part of your Type II evidence.

124
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Your lab exercise is to generate a monthly integrity report.
Verify that all checks pass.
Store the report in your immutable S3 bucket.

125
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
In the next lecture, we will run the tamper detection demonstration.
To prove the system works to your auditor.

