[## LECTURE 4.7 — THE TAMPER-DETECTION DEMONSTRATION]

126
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Before submitting to your auditor, run the tamper-detection test.
Prove that any modification to analysis_history is detected.
This demonstration should be part of your auditor walkthrough.

127
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
First, insert a legitimate record.
Call the API or insert directly through the repository.
Capture the record ID.

128
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Second, record the current hash.
Query the current_hash for the record.
Note the value.

129
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Third, attempt a direct UPDATE.
Update the answer column on the record.
The trigger should block it with an error message.

130
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
If the UPDATE fails with a clear error, the trigger is working.
If it succeeds, your trigger is missing or disabled.
Fix that before proceeding.

131
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Fourth, simulate a DBA bypassing the trigger.
Set session_replication_role to replica.
This temporarily disables triggers.

132
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Then run the UPDATE again.
This time it will succeed because triggers are disabled.
This simulates a malicious superuser.

133
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Set session_replication_role back to default.
Now run hash chain verification.

134
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The verification should detect that the chain is broken.
chain_valid should be false.
first_broken_at should be the ID of the tampered record.

135
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
This proves that even if a superuser bypasses the trigger,
the hash chain detects the modification immediately.
The signing key lives in Vault. Without it, an attacker cannot recompute valid hashes or forge signatures.

136
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Run this demonstration in your staging environment.
Document the steps and outputs.
Include the demonstration in your audit evidence package.

137
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
